Put a large #saucepan{} of @water{50%ml} with a pinch of @salt{pinch} on to boil. When boiling, add the @egg noodle nests{2} and cook for ~{4%minutes}. Drain in a #sieve{}, then return to the pan (off the heat) and refill with cold water. (This will stop them sticking together!).

Meanwhile, chop the @British turkey steaks{2} into 2cm chunks. IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Trim and peel the @carrot{1} then use a #vegetable peeler{} to peel long ribbons along its length. Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips. Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed then finely chop. Trim and finely slice the @spring onion{2}. Peel and grate the @ginger{1/2%small piece}.

Heat a #frying pan{} until hot with @oil{}. Add the turkey and cook until browned, ~{2%minutes}.

Stir in the ginger, half the spring onion and a pinch of chilli (careful - you can always add more later!) and stir-fry for another ~{1%minute}.

Now pour in the @soy sauce{25%ml} and water, bring to the boil then lower the heat and bubble until the liquid has reduced slightly, ~{1-2%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The turkey is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Drain the noodles again and stir into the frying pan. Heat until piping hot. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Squeeze over the juice of the @lime{1/2}.

Serve the turkey stir-fry in #bowls{} finished with a sprinkling of remaining spring onion and chilli if liked. Enjoy!

> Super lean and packed with protein, turkey is a great addition to this weeknight favourite and works brilliantly with the rich umami flavours in this dish. Crunchy carrot and red peppers (packed with Vitamin C) give the dish a lovely texture, whilst ginger and red chilli give it a welcome kick of heat.